He was there for five hours.
-[Jim] Mhmm.

952
00:47:26,718 --> 00:47:31,098
-[Laurette] We took him down,
unpacked him.

953
00:47:31,098 --> 00:47:33,559
Thought everything
was fine.

954
00:47:33,559 --> 00:47:36,895
Five hours later we got a call
from campus police

955
00:47:36,895 --> 00:47:39,898
that he was
in the hospital.

956
00:47:39,898 --> 00:47:45,279
He had taken too many Xanax,
which was what he thought was

957
00:47:45,279 --> 00:47:47,155
going to help him, you know,

958
00:47:47,155 --> 00:47:52,578
struggling with the anxiety, and
um...

959
00:47:52,578 --> 00:47:57,791
He was in I.C.U. for probably 24
hours. Something like that.

960
00:47:57,791 --> 00:48:03,755
So it kind of all started to
unravel, freshman year,

961
00:48:03,755 --> 00:48:06,341
and then from that point we
brought him home

962
00:48:06,341 --> 00:48:08,635
and had him do online courses.

963
00:48:08,635 --> 00:48:11,555
-[Jim] So we got there and
talked to the doctor

964
00:48:11,555 --> 00:48:13,849
and one of the 
comments the doctor

965
00:48:13,849 --> 00:48:18,687
made when he came in was
he felt like a failure.

966
00:48:18,687 --> 00:48:22,274
So this was in the 
midst of his stupor and

967
00:48:22,274 --> 00:48:23,817
so when he came out
of it they

968
00:48:23,817 --> 00:48:26,570
actually had a
psychiatrist evaluate him

969
00:48:26,570 --> 00:48:30,741
because he felt the way he did.
And uh, their suggestion

970
00:48:30,741 --> 00:48:34,119
was to take him home for a
couple weeks

971
00:48:34,119 --> 00:48:37,122
and then send him back, well you
can't really do that in college

972
00:48:37,122 --> 00:48:42,294
so we took him home, he got 
online schooling, and then we

973
00:48:42,294 --> 00:48:47,674
proceeded to look for a
psychologist and a psychiatrist

974
00:48:47,674 --> 00:48:51,011
for him to talk to,
that lasted probably the next

975
00:48:51,011 --> 00:48:53,263
five or six months he was going
once a week.

976
00:48:53,263 --> 00:48:54,973
Josh communicated but

977
00:48:54,973 --> 00:49:04,524
it's also the belief that

978
00:49:04,524 --> 00:49:08,111
we never knew the severity
nor I don't think he knew how to

979
00:49:08,111 --> 00:49:12,199
communicate the severity of it.

980
00:49:12,199 --> 00:49:14,493
He would communicate,
he would

981
00:49:14,493 --> 00:49:16,203
at times try
to self-medicate

982
00:49:16,203 --> 00:49:20,207
and every time he came out of
that self-medication I call it

983
00:49:20,207 --> 00:49:23,960
he would talk and...

984
00:49:23,960 --> 00:49:26,963
but he never...

985
00:49:26,963 --> 00:49:29,841
I don't want to say he wanted to
be a burden to anybody but

986
00:49:29,841 --> 00:49:33,887
I also don't think he knew
how to fix it.

987
00:49:33,887 --> 00:49:36,973
He didn't, he didn't want to...
he didn't feel comfortable

988
00:49:36,973 --> 00:49:38,767
communicating or he didn't
communicate it

989
00:49:38,767 --> 00:49:40,227
'cause when he did 
communicate it

990
00:49:40,227 --> 00:49:43,105
he couldn't, he couldn't
express it.

991
00:49:43,105 --> 00:49:47,150
-[Laurette] Never one time did
Josh ever say

992
00:49:47,150 --> 00:49:49,945
"I don't want to be here."
Not one time.

993
00:49:54,408 --> 00:50:00,539
-[Laurette] He took his life in
the garden that he made for me

994
00:50:00,539 --> 00:50:06,169
'cause I think he was comforted
by being there.

995
00:50:06,169 --> 00:50:14,469
Josh died February 6th of this
year. Um...

996
00:50:22,060 --> 00:50:27,607
I'll never be the same.
I'll never be the same person.

997
00:50:27,607 --> 00:50:35,282
He'll never be the same.

998
00:50:35,282 --> 00:50:41,747
It's difficult to function 
most days

999
00:50:41,747 --> 00:50:45,709
and I think someone
that takes...

1000
00:50:45,709 --> 00:50:48,712
is considering
taking their life

1001
00:50:48,712 --> 00:50:51,840
you need to understand
what you're leaving.

1002
00:50:51,840 --> 00:50:55,969
And when you make that kind
of decision

1003
00:50:55,969 --> 00:50:59,556
I know sometimes
I hear people say

1004
00:50:59,556 --> 00:51:04,019
"It's like something snapped
in them and they just did it."

1005
00:51:04,019 --> 00:51:07,856
Josh talked to me that night.
He said "Mom, you know

1006
00:51:07,856 --> 00:51:09,900
I've been thinking about it all
all day today." and I was like

1007
00:51:09,900 --> 00:51:12,611
"You know what Josh?
We'll put a plan together.

1008
00:51:12,611 --> 00:51:14,654
We will do something.

1009
00:51:14,654 --> 00:51:16,490
We will go talk to
somebody else.

1010
00:51:16,490 --> 00:51:19,117
We will...we'll do whatever
we gotta do

1011
00:51:19,117 --> 00:51:23,371
because we get up,
this family gets up.

1012
00:51:23,371 --> 00:51:25,624
[Laurette] No matter what,
we will get through it.

1013
00:51:25,624 --> 00:51:27,751
We will do what we have to do

1014
00:51:27,751 --> 00:51:32,380
and it doesn't matter.
If you're not good tomorrow

1015
00:51:32,380 --> 00:51:35,884
we'll figure it out.
And as far as I was concerned

1016
00:51:35,884 --> 00:51:38,929
we had it figured out.

1017
00:51:38,929 --> 00:51:42,933
Josh could not

1018
00:51:42,933 --> 00:51:47,604
be the burden that he... He
didn't want to be a burden to us

1019
00:51:47,604 --> 00:51:50,774
and honestly I don't care
who you are.

1020
00:51:50,774 --> 00:51:55,445
You're not a burden
to your family ever.

1021
00:51:55,445 --> 00:51:57,614
Ever.

1022
00:51:57,614 --> 00:51:59,199
We, you know, there wasn't...

1023
00:51:59,199 --> 00:52:04,830
There wasn't anything
that we wouldn't have done

1024
00:52:04,830 --> 00:52:06,915
because we are
forever changed.

1025
00:52:06,915 --> 00:52:09,584
[Laurette] I'm not saying that
we're um...

1026
00:52:09,584 --> 00:52:12,963
we're not living because
we're surviving.

1027
00:52:12,963 --> 00:52:17,926
That's what we're doing.
And for another parent,

1028
00:52:17,926 --> 00:52:21,429
another sister, another brother
to have to do it,

1029
00:52:21,429 --> 00:52:24,099
we don't want that.

1030
00:52:24,099 --> 00:52:30,063
That's why we're willing to tell
this story to somebody.

1031
00:52:30,063 --> 00:52:35,026
I don't want to watch somebody
else do what we're doing.

1032
00:52:47,706 --> 00:52:50,375
[Jamie] There's a lot of forms
of brokenness on this planet

1033
00:52:50,375 --> 00:52:52,794
that people are okay
talking about

1034
00:52:52,794 --> 00:52:55,338
and for some reason
when it comes to depression,

1035
00:52:55,338 --> 00:52:59,134
when it comes to self injury
or addiction or suicide

1036
00:52:59,134 --> 00:53:02,929
these are things that are often
not talked about and we love

1037
00:53:02,929 --> 00:53:06,266
the idea of that changing and
think that honesty is the

1038
00:53:06,266 --> 00:53:09,561
beginning, honesty is really
contagious and disarming and

1039
00:53:09,561 --> 00:53:11,938
has a way of letting people
know it's okay to go there

1040
00:53:11,938 --> 00:53:14,232
and you're not alone
in how you feel.

1041
00:53:14,774 --> 00:53:19,696
When you're in the midst of all
of this pain and insecurity

1042
00:53:19,696 --> 00:53:23,199
and fear it can be hard to reach
out for help or even have

1043
00:53:23,199 --> 00:53:27,746
a conversation with one of
your closest friends about

1044
00:53:27,746 --> 00:53:32,334
what's going on in your own mind
and in your own feelings because

1045
00:53:32,334 --> 00:53:35,587
it can be hard to value
yourself enough

1046
00:53:35,587 --> 00:53:37,589
to receive the
help that you need.

1047
00:53:37,589 --> 00:53:39,591
I'm glad I got help when I did

1048
00:53:39,591 --> 00:53:42,135
but I wish I had gotten
help sooner

1049
00:53:42,135 --> 00:53:44,429
maybe if I had things
wouldn't have gotten so bad.

1050
00:53:44,429 --> 00:53:46,473
If I... If any of my children
ever went though something

1051
00:53:46,473 --> 00:53:48,558
like that, I would um...

1052
00:53:48,558 --> 00:53:51,353
definitely try to be as
emotionally available

1053
00:53:51,353 --> 00:53:55,774
and just present as I could to
help them and then also get them

1054
00:53:55,774 --> 00:53:58,693
any kind of professional help
that I was able to

1055
00:53:58,693 --> 00:54:02,614
so they wouldn't have to
go through it on their own.

1056
00:54:02,614 --> 00:54:05,575
I had the privilege of visiting
the White House about a

1057
00:54:05,575 --> 00:54:09,913
year and a half ago and was part
of a group of about 150 people

1058
00:54:09,913 --> 00:54:12,165
who work in the realm of
mental health and

1059
00:54:12,165 --> 00:54:14,417
got to hear from the President
and the Vice President

1060
00:54:14,417 --> 00:54:16,336
and all sorts of folks
were there and...

1061
00:54:16,336 --> 00:54:19,547
and the day was really meant to
represent and indicate

1062
00:54:19,547 --> 00:54:21,967
the idea that things were
changing and that this

1063
00:54:21,967 --> 00:54:26,096
is a priority to the leaders of
this country and that it should

1064
00:54:26,096 --> 00:54:29,683
be easier, it should be more
comfortable, more accessible

1065
00:54:29,683 --> 00:54:30,976
for people to get help.

1066
00:54:31,309 --> 00:54:34,229
Even though three quarters of
mental illnesses emerge by the

1067
00:54:34,229 --> 00:54:37,899
end of... by the age of 24,

1068
00:54:37,899 --> 00:54:40,360
only about half of children with
mental-health problems

1069
00:54:40,360 --> 00:54:42,195
receive treatment.

1070
00:54:43,196 --> 00:54:44,823
Now think about it,
we wouldn't accept it if

1071
00:54:44,823 --> 00:54:51,121
only 40% of Americans with
cancers got treatment.

1072
00:54:51,121 --> 00:54:53,081
We wouldn't accept it if only
half of young people with

1073
00:54:53,081 --> 00:54:55,583
diabetes got help.

1074
00:54:55,583 --> 00:54:58,086
Why should we accept it when it
comes to mental-health?

1075
00:54:58,086 --> 00:54:59,963
Doesn't make any sense.

1076
00:55:00,422 --> 00:55:04,009
In some cases when a condition
goes untreated it can lead to

1077
00:55:04,009 --> 00:55:06,720
tragedy on a larger scale.

1078
00:55:06,720 --> 00:55:10,265
We can do something about
stories like these.

1079
00:55:10,265 --> 00:55:14,060
In many cases treatment is
available and effective.

1080
00:55:14,060 --> 00:55:17,439
The awareness level has to be
higher, it has to be.

1081
00:55:17,439 --> 00:55:20,316
There are... We hear it every
day, somebody got bullied

1082
00:55:20,316 --> 00:55:22,152
to death or just gave up.

1083
00:55:22,152 --> 00:55:26,281
It's an epidemic, it's a very
sad situation

1084
00:55:26,281 --> 00:55:28,324
and it's avoidable,
it's preventable.

1085
00:55:28,324 --> 00:55:30,910
It can take a few tries
to find something that works

1086
00:55:30,910 --> 00:55:35,415
and it's a combination of
professional help, of therapy,

1087
00:55:35,415 --> 00:55:38,501
of medication, and even
therapists. Sometimes you don't

1088
00:55:38,501 --> 00:55:40,754
click with the first person you
talk to but it doesn't mean it's

1089
00:55:40,754 --> 00:55:41,880
not gonna work.

1090
00:55:41,880 --> 00:55:44,632
And outside of that, just
finding something in life that

1091
00:55:44,632 --> 00:55:46,676
you're passionate about,
something that you can really

1092
00:55:46,676 --> 00:55:49,888
work towards. For me that's
photography and music.

1093
00:55:49,888 --> 00:55:54,726
If I looked back at myself when
I was 14, when I was depressed

1094
00:55:54,726 --> 00:55:59,814
and struggling so much, I think
that girl would see me now and

1095
00:55:59,814 --> 00:56:02,525
be amazed at what she's doing.

1096
00:56:02,525 --> 00:56:06,488
I'm doing things now that when I
was 14 I wanted to do,

1097
00:56:06,488 --> 00:56:11,201
I dreamed of doing, but I never

1098
00:56:11,201 --> 00:56:13,578
took the steps to do it when I
was younger because I thought

1099
00:56:13,578 --> 00:56:17,665
I couldn't. I've done music
photography and interviews with

1100
00:56:17,665 --> 00:56:19,459
people that I never would have
dreamed of, some of the

1101
00:56:19,459 --> 00:56:22,045
biggest artists in the world.
People I've looked up to for

1102
00:56:22,045 --> 00:56:26,257
years and getting to photograph
these artists just makes

1103
00:56:26,257 --> 00:56:28,009
everything come full circle.

1104
00:56:28,009 --> 00:56:31,137
Finding my passion really
helped so much.

1105
00:56:31,137 --> 00:56:33,098
It gives you something
to work for

1106
00:56:33,098 --> 00:56:35,141
and it gives you a reason
to live.

1107
00:56:35,141 --> 00:56:38,728
Just know that there are people
around that are gonna support

1108
00:56:38,728 --> 00:56:40,730
you and are gonna help you,
you just need to find them

1109
00:56:40,730 --> 00:56:46,569
and reach out to them 'cause
there are always people around

1110
00:56:46,569 --> 00:56:49,697
that want to be there for you.
That want to help you.

1111
00:56:49,697 --> 00:56:51,783
I didn't feel like I had anyone.

1112
00:56:51,783 --> 00:56:53,785
I felt completely alone.

1113
00:56:53,785 --> 00:56:58,164
I felt like I had no family,
no friends, no support

1114
00:56:58,164 --> 00:57:02,627
but looking around
I really did.

1115
00:57:02,627 --> 00:57:07,215
I... I had those people
and everyone does.

1116
00:57:07,215 --> 00:57:10,260
You're helping them to see that
you're not alone, you have...

1117
00:57:10,260 --> 00:57:13,680
And to finally see kids that
have gotten to a point

1118
00:57:13,680 --> 00:57:15,974
where they say "My friends are
what saved my life."

1119
00:57:15,974 --> 00:57:19,185
You know, "My support system is
what saved my life."

1120
00:57:19,185 --> 00:57:20,436
That's why we do it.

1121
00:57:20,854 --> 00:57:22,856
-[Jim] If you're not doing
anything to help your kid

1122
00:57:22,856 --> 00:57:27,318
we would have loved that
opportunity.

1123
00:57:27,318 --> 00:57:28,111
-[Laurette] There wasn't...
There wasn't anything...

1124
00:57:28,111 --> 00:57:30,655
-[Jim] We don't have that
opportunity anymore.

1125
00:57:30,655 --> 00:57:33,575
And if your child's in crisis

1126
00:57:33,575 --> 00:57:39,789
and to the point of voluntary
or involuntary treatment,

1127
00:57:39,789 --> 00:57:44,961
there should be no other option
because as a parent

1128
00:57:44,961 --> 00:57:49,674
It's our belief, we were given
the gift of life with these

1129
00:57:49,674 --> 00:57:52,510
children. They are not here for
us.

1130
00:57:52,510 --> 00:57:56,181
We are here for them if they
are in crisis of any kind.

1131
00:57:56,181 --> 00:57:59,100
It is our responsibility to do
the very best we can

1132
00:57:59,100 --> 00:58:02,979
and if somebody comes and...
If one of your children come and

1133
00:58:02,979 --> 00:58:06,566
blatantly tell you what
they're thinking.

1134
00:58:06,566 --> 00:58:09,402
It is our responsibility as
parents to do everything

1135
00:58:09,402 --> 00:58:12,363
possible to get them the help
that they deserve.

1136
00:58:12,363 --> 00:58:15,450
I think honesty is contagious
and that so much of it starts

1137
00:58:15,450 --> 00:58:18,661
there with just trying to create
environments and relationships

1138
00:58:18,661 --> 00:58:22,540
and conversations where people
know that they can be honest

1139
00:58:22,540 --> 00:58:25,460
about their struggles and
to stop painting a picture

1140
00:58:25,460 --> 00:58:28,755
of this world where everyone's
okay all the time and...

1141
00:58:28,755 --> 00:58:31,216
but that we're people and as
people we encounter pain,

1142
00:58:31,216 --> 00:58:32,884
we encounter loss,

1143
00:58:32,884 --> 00:58:36,429
we encounter depression and it's
okay to be honest about that.

1144
00:58:36,429 --> 00:58:40,141
And I think that's how things
maybe begin to change is just

1145
00:58:40,141 --> 00:58:43,102
creating an environment where we
go "Hey, if you need help,

1146
00:58:43,102 --> 00:58:44,854
it's okay, it's part of
being human.

1147
00:58:44,854 --> 00:58:47,148
It's okay to say
you need help.

1148
00:58:47,148 --> 00:58:51,444
I know that I will always
struggle with depression.

1149
00:58:51,444 --> 00:58:54,906
It's a part of me, but
it is not who I am.

1150
00:58:54,906 --> 00:58:57,951
Although it can become
overwhelming some days

1151
00:58:57,951 --> 00:59:01,454
and although some days the
symptoms feel like

1152
00:59:01,454 --> 00:59:04,874
they're paralyzing me

1153
00:59:04,874 --> 00:59:10,588
I've reached out enough to have
people to pull me out from

